==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic, cognate with Old Saxon [[alf]] (German [[Alp]] ‘nightmare’), Old Norse [[álfr]] (Swedish [[elf]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /ælf/

===Noun===
'''ælf''' ''m''
# an [[elf]], a [[fairy]] or [[incubus]]
#:''Wið ælfe guid myrran on win.''  [To protect] against an elf, rub myrrh in wine.

